### Tested versions

Tested in:

- 4.3 stable
- 4.4 stable
- 4.5 stable

### System information

Godot v4.5.stable - Windows 11 (build 26100) - Multi-window, 1 monitor - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 5080 (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.7688) - 12th Gen Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-12700K (20 threads) - 31.76 GiB memory

Tested with a Valve Index with SteamVR.

### Issue description

When viewed in VR, shaders which use `CAMERA_VISIBLE_LAYERS` to change their rendering based on the camera's cull mask look incorrect. It seems that CAMERA_VISIBLE_LAYERS is always set to the default value, where all layers are active, in VR.

For example, with a VR camera that only has the first layer (bit 0) set, this shader produces red, although it should produce blue (since bit 1 == 2^1 == 2 is not set):

```
void fragment() {
	if ((int(CAMERA_VISIBLE_LAYERS) & 2) == 2) {
		ALBEDO = vec3(1.0, 0.0, 0.0);
	} else {
		ALBEDO = vec3(0.0, 0.0, 1.0);
	}
}
```

On the other hand, setting the object's render layers via the UI for entirely hiding objects does work as expected for VR cameras. This seems to only affect the `CAMERA_VISIBLE_LAYERS`  shader parameter.

### Steps to reproduce

Run the MRP (which contains the shader shown above) with a VR headset and observe that the normal camera shows a blue cube, while the VR camera with the same cull mask displays a red cube. Both cameras correctly hide the other cube.

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[vr-render-layer-bug.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/22883490/vr-render-layer-bug.zip)
